The allusion to the disciples of Jesus is unavoidable, and Zarathustra considers the appropriate strategy would be to acquire ‘disciples. Indeed, the best kind of disciple is one who can remain ‘faithful’ to him or herself and even attack an idea to make it stronger. Therefore, calling oneself a ‘disciple’ of Dionysus, this is a way of thinking about one's role in the health and growth of the human organism, and gratitude towards such a fortunate situation. The idea is that being a ‘disciple’ is indeed an step forward in many ways, including understanding which is a more permanent state and thus also capable of creating and accelerating further the decline of existing forms of power. Nevertheless, it is a ‘deformation’ from the Apollonian awareness of God and continually growing, and thus, is also a sign of decadence. Also, being a ‘disciple’ of the notion of education, from a higher perspective, is the only way of living life free from chance – and thus, from a view to the values itself. An ‘opposite ideal’ is knowledge itself, an acquisition of such a knowledge. However, it has to be free from chance, since that which is not already a reality. Not all creation is thus an 'opposite ideal'. 

